How Fast Could 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFF8FD6D4CD4E130FC08FEE5" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[486,908,294,341]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D4CD4E130FC08FEE5" bold="true" box="[486,908,294,341]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Tyrannosaurus rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Run?
</heading>
</subSubSection>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFF8FD6D4F19E161FDCEFE00" blockId="1.[555,950,374,450]" box="[555,586,375,432]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">•</paragraph>
<subSubSection id="C4E157CBFFF8FD6D4F78E160FD71FE72" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" type="description">
<paragraph id="8C440440FFF8FD6D4F78E160FD71FE72" blockId="1.[555,950,374,450]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">A new biomechanics model finds that T. rex lacked large enough leg muscles to run fast.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C4E157CBFFF8FD6E4D52E170FB0FFBCD" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="19" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" type="description">
<paragraph id="8C440440FFF8FD6D4D52E170FF52FD12" blockId="1.[96,512,358,912]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D4D52E170FF31FECF" bold="true" box="[96,181,358,424]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">From</emphasis>
Saturday-morning television shows to Hollywood blockbusters, dinosaurs are perennial favorites for inspiring people’s curiosity. And top- ping the fascination list is usually 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFF8FD6D4D52E1F9FEB6FDB4" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[96,306,495,516]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D4D52E1F9FEB6FDB4" box="[96,306,495,516]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Tyrannosaurus rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the six-ton giant that reigned over the Upper Cretaceous Period 65 million years ago, moving around on hind legs more than 2.5 meters long and devouring less fortunate creatures with its powerful jaws.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFF8FD6D4DB2E2B1FE3CFCEA" blockId="1.[96,512,358,912]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Although the fossil record provides clues about some aspects of dinosaur existence, insights into many others must be tortuously teased out of uncov- ered bones and footprints. Many questions lack direct answers. For example, how fast could dinosaurs move?</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFF8FD6D4DB2E376FEA9FAAC" blockId="1.[96,512,358,912]" lastBlockId="1.[96,443,916,1625]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
That question has proved easier to answer for smaller dinosaurs, whose fossilized footprints contain speed information. In the mid1970s, McNeill Alexander (Uni- versity of Leeds) derived a method for estimating speed from the ratio of the stride length to the leg length (which can be determined from recovered bones or estimated from the footprint size). 
<bibRefCitation id="E86A79B1FFF8FD6D4C0CE497FEC2FB3D" author="R. M. Alexander" box="[318,326,1153,1165]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" pagination="129" part="261" refId="ref2076" refString="1. R. M. Alexander, Nature 261, 129 (1976)." title="Nature" type="journal article" year="1976">1</bibRefCitation>
So-called trackways containing stride records have provided evidence for running (having a suspend- ed, aerial phase) for many bipedal dinosaurs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFF8FD6D4DB2E537FEBFF993" blockId="1.[96,443,916,1625]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
No trackway evidence of running by larger animals such as 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFF8FD6D4D4DE540FF3FFADB" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[127,187,1366,1387]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D4D4DE540FF3FFADB" box="[127,187,1366,1387]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">T. rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been found, which is not unexpected. It’s rare to find fossil beds large enough to span the stride of a running T. rex. In addition, most creatures spend much more time walking than running, so any running trackways are rare.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFF8FD6D4DB2E63FFE7BF893" blockId="1.[96,443,916,1625]" lastBlockId="1.[96,513,1630,1917]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
Most estimates of the speed of 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFF8FD6D4DB7E652FEB7F9E9" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[133,307,1604,1625]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D4DB7E652FEB7F9E9" box="[133,307,1604,1625]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Tyrannosaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and other large dinosaurs have instead come from various comparisons to other vertebrates. Noting the similarity of 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFF8FD6D4D52E6B8FF21F973" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[96,165,1710,1731]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D4D52E6B8FF21F973" box="[96,165,1710,1731]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">T. rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
skeletal anatomy to that of extant birds and other fast runners, Gregory Paul and Robert Bakker have suggested that 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFF8FD6D4C3AE6EBFEC7F8A2" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[264,323,1789,1810]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D4C3AE6EBFEC7F8A2" box="[264,323,1789,1810]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">T. rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
would have been able to run at least 20 m/s (45 mph). 
<bibRefCitation id="E86A79B1FFF8FD6D4CC5E701FE7BF893" author="G. S. Paul" box="[503,511,1815,1827]" journalOrPublisher="Gaia" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" pagination="257" part="15" refId="ref2092" refString="2. G. S. Paul, Gaia 15, 257 (2000)." type="journal article" unsafe="true" year="2000">2</bibRefCitation>
</paragraph>
<caption id="D88454C8FFF8FD6D4F11E642FCF4F8EA" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3961002" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3961002" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3961002/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" startId="1.[547,623,1620,1641]" targetBox="[468,1044,933,1607]" targetPageId="1">
<paragraph id="8C440440FFF8FD6D4F11E642FCF4F8EA" blockId="1.[547,955,1620,1882]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D4F11E642FC16F9D8" bold="true" box="[547,914,1620,1641]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">FIGURE 1. IN A FREE- BODY DIAGRAM</emphasis>
for a running tyrannosaur, the angles of the leg joints (top) are critical parameters. In addi- tion to the forces and torques produced by leg muscles, external forces (bottom) including the weights of the body (
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D4E02E6CCFCC1F95F" box="[816,837,1754,1775]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Ƒ</emphasis>
b), thigh (
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D4EADE6CCFC30F95F" box="[927,948,1754,1775]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Ƒ</emphasis>
t), shank (
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D4F4AE6E2FD09F8B9" box="[632,653,1780,1801]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Ƒ</emphasis>
s), and metatarsus (
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D4E72E6E2FCD1F8B9" box="[832,853,1780,1801]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Ƒ</emphasis>
m), as well as the ground reaction force (GRF) that acts a distance 
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D4F9FE73CFD39F88F" box="[685,701,1834,1855]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">R</emphasis>
from the toe joint must be incorporated. (Adapted from ref. 6.)
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFF8FD6D4DB2E724FCE1FCED" blockId="1.[96,513,1630,1917]" lastBlockId="1.[544,961,495,915]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
Applying more physics-based arguments, others have proposed slower maximum speeds. Based on the maximum transverse forces that 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFF8FD6D4EB1E1E6FC44FDB5" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[899,960,496,517]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D4EB1E1E6FC44FDB5" box="[899,960,496,517]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">T. rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
bones could have withstood, Alexander has argued that it was capable of a modest run at best. 
<bibRefCitation id="E86A79B1FFF8FD6D4E1CE228FCB2FDFA" author="R. M. Alexander" box="[814,822,574,586]" journalOrPublisher="Zoolog. J. Linnean Soc." pageId="1" pageNumber="18" pagination="1" part="83" refId="ref2126" refString="3. R. M. Alexander, Zoolog. J. Linnean Soc. 83, 1 (1985)." type="journal article" year="1985">3</bibRefCitation>
Per Christiansen (University of Copenhagen), quantifing such arguments, estimated that 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFF8FD6D4F4DE299FD3BFD14" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[639,703,655,676]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D4F4DE299FD3BFD14" box="[639,703,655,676]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">T. rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could walk at 10 m/s (22 mph)—still far from slow. 
<bibRefCitation id="E86A79B1FFF8FD6D4E5BE2BEFCF5FD04" author="P. Christiansen" box="[873,881,680,692]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" pagination="241" part="15" refId="ref2148" refString="4. P. Christiansen, Gaia 15, 241 (2000)." title="Gaia" type="journal article" year="2000">4</bibRefCitation>
James Farlow (Indiana–Purdue University) and colleagues 
<bibRefCitation id="E86A79B1FFF8FD6D4FF0E2CBFD4EFD59" author="J. O. Farlow &amp; M. B. Smith &amp; J. M. Robinson" box="[706,714,733,745]" journalOrPublisher="J. Vert. Paleontol" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" pagination="713" part="15" refId="ref2162" refString="5. J. O. Farlow, M. B. Smith, J. M. Robinson, J. Vert. Paleontol. 15, 713 (1995)." type="journal article" year="1995">5</bibRefCitation>
have suggested that a fast-running 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFF8FD6D4F86E2EFFD77FCBE" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[692,755,761,782]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D4F86E2EFFD77FCBE" box="[692,755,761,782]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">T. rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
would have experienced fatally large forces if it had tripped, so they concluded it likely moved no faster than 10 m/s.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFF8FD6D4F72E374FBE0FD2F" blockId="1.[544,961,495,915]" lastBlockId="1.[992,1409,358,672]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
Working at the University of California, Berkeley, John Hutchinson (now at Stanford University) and Mariano Garcia (now at Borg Warner Automotive in New York) recently offered a new approach for analyzing possible speeds of 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFF8FD6D498CE1C7FA85FE56" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[1214,1281,465,486]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D498CE1C7FA85FE56" box="[1214,1281,465,486]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">T. rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and other bipeds, based on a biomechanical model for determining the minimum mass of leg extensor muscle required for an animal to run. 
<bibRefCitation id="E86A79B1FFF8FD6D49F2E22FFB4CFDF5" author="J. R. Hutchinson &amp; M. Garcia" box="[1216,1224,569,581]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" pagination="1018" part="415" refId="ref2195" refString="6. J. R. Hutchinson, M. Garcia, Nature 415, 1018 (2002)." title="Nature" type="journal article" year="2002">6</bibRefCitation>
With this model, the pair found that 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFF8FD6D49F9E243FA8FFDDA" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[1227,1291,597,618]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D49F9E243FA8FFDDA" box="[1227,1291,597,618]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">T. rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could not have had strong enough legs to be a fast runner.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFF8FD6D4ED2E2A2FB23FD7F" blockId="1.[992,1191,692,719]" box="[992,1191,692,719]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D4ED2E2A2FB23FD7F" bold="true" box="[992,1191,692,719]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">Scaling muscles</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFF8FD6D4ED2E2C1FB4CFC46" blockId="1.[992,1408,727,908]" lastBlockId="1.[1071,1409,913,1624]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
Underlying this new model is the observation that muscles in vertebrate animals generate remarkably uniform maximum force per unit cross section, about 300 kN/m2. Given that evolution has conserved this muscle property, Hutchinson and Garcia argue it’s reasonable to assume that the muscles of dinosaurs such as 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFF8FD6D485EE3BAFBCBFC6B" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D485EE3BAFBCBFC6B" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">T. rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had similar force-generating capability.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFF8FD6D497DE3EDFACAFAD9" blockId="1.[1071,1409,913,1624]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
One consequence of this 
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D491DE403FBC0FB26" bold="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
uniformity is that muscle strength increases more slowly than muscle mass as body size increases, as roughly the 
<bibRefCitation id="E86A79B1FFF8FD6D491DE469FBB3FB3B" author="G. S. Paul" box="[1071,1079,1151,1163]" journalOrPublisher="Gaia" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" pagination="257" part="15" refId="ref2092" refString="2. G. S. Paul, Gaia 15, 257 (2000). R. T. Bakker, Dinosaur Heresies, William Morrow, New York (1986)." title="Dinosaur Heresies" type="journal article" year="2000">2</bibRefCitation>
/ power rather than linearly. 
<bibRefCitation id="E86A79B1FFF8FD6D490EE49CFBC0FB26" author="R. M. Alexander" box="[1084,1092,1162,1174]" journalOrPublisher="Zoolog. J. Linnean Soc." pageId="1" pageNumber="18" pagination="1" part="83" refId="ref2126" refString="3. R. M. Alexander, Zoolog. J. Linnean Soc. 83, 1 (1985)." type="journal article" year="1985">3</bibRefCitation>
</emphasis>
Thus, as body size increases, the muscle mass needed to support and move it increases even faster. This scaling dif- ference, well-known for decades, is at the core of the researchers’ conclusion that 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFF8FD6D485EE52CFBD4FAD9" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D485EE52CFBD4FAD9" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">T. rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was not a fast runner.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFF8FD6D497DE578FB4AF9C3" blockId="1.[1071,1409,913,1624]" lastBlockId="1.[992,1408,1629,1916]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">
Hutchinson and Garcia use a two-dimensional free-body 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFF8FD6D491DE5B5FA04FA09" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[1071,1408,1443,1465]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="1" pageNumber="18" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFF8FD6D491DE5B5FA04FA09" box="[1071,1408,1443,1465]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">diagram to determine the min-</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
imum muscle mass per leg that’s needed at midstride to maintain quasistatic equilibrium, factoring in the forces and torques from various muscles, limb segment weights, and the ground (see 
<figureCitation id="14C018C5FFF8FD6D495AE64BFB39F9C3" box="[1128,1213,1629,1651]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[547,623,1620,1641]" captionTargetBox="[468,1044,933,1607]" captionTargetId="graphics@1.[468,1044,933,1609]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. IN A FREE-BODY DIAGRAM for a running tyrannosaur, the angles of the leg joints (top) are critical parameters. In addi- tion to the forces and torques produced by leg muscles, external forces (bottom) including the weights of the body (Ƒb), thigh (Ƒt), shank (Ƒs), and metatarsus (Ƒm), as well as the ground reaction force (GRF) that acts a distance R from the toe joint must be incorporated. (Adapted from ref. 6.)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3961002" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3961002/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">figure 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFF8FD6D4932E66EFB77F8CC" blockId="1.[992,1408,1629,1916]" pageId="1" pageNumber="18">At the midpoint of the running stride, the body is at its lowest point, accelerating upward. The necessary upward force comes from the ground. For extant bipeds at a fast run, this ground reaction force (GRF) is about 2.5 times the body weight, relatively inde- pendent of species or mass. Hutchinson and Garcia therefore adopted this relation for their calculations.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFFBFD6E4D92E049FEFEFD42" blockId="2.[128,449,95,860]" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">
To translate this GRF into a forward velocity, the researchers applied the notion of dynamic similarity. Originally proposed by Alexander, 
<bibRefCitation id="E86A79B1FFFBFD6E4DC6E0F5FF78FF5F" author="R. M. Alexander" box="[244,252,227,239]" journalOrPublisher="Zoolog. J. Linnean Soc." pageId="2" pageNumber="19" pagination="1" part="83" refId="ref2126" refString="3. R. M. Alexander, Zoolog. J. Linnean Soc. 83, 1 (1985)." type="journal article" year="1985">3</bibRefCitation>
this concept considers the ratio between an animal’s kinetic and potential energy as expressed in the Froude number, Fr = 
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFFBFD6E4CB1E158FE0BFED3" box="[387,399,334,355]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">Ʋ</emphasis>
2/ 
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFFBFD6E4CACE158FE3EFED3" box="[414,442,334,355]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">gh</emphasis>
, where 
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFFBFD6E4DFBE17FFF51FECE" box="[201,213,361,382]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">Ʋ</emphasis>
is the forward velocity, 
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFFBFD6E4D97E195FF36FE28" box="[165,178,387,408]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">g</emphasis>
the acceleration due to gravity, and 
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFFBFD6E4C3BE18BFE9CFE02" box="[265,280,413,434]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">h</emphasis>
the hip height. Animals moving with the same Froude number should have similar gaits and exert similar relative forces. A fastrunning ostrich experiences a GRF of 2.7 times its body weight at Fr = 16; a 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFFBFD6E4C4CE24EFE3BFDDD" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[382,447,600,621]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="2" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFFBFD6E4C4CE24EFE3BFDDD" box="[382,447,600,621]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">T. rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with a similar relative GRF should have a similar Froude number, which corresponds to about 20 m/s—in line with the faster speed estimates.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFFBFD6E4D32E068FF80FFCF" box="[0,4,126,127]" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">-</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFFBFD6E4D32E182FF80FE25" box="[0,4,404,405]" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFFBFD6E4D32E226FF80FD81" box="[0,4,560,561]" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">kg</paragraph>
<caption id="D88454C8FFFBFD6E4CEFE250FD29FCA7" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3961004" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3961004" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3961004/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="19" startId="2.[477,555,582,603]" targetBox="[484,1113,99,567]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph id="8C440440FFFBFD6E4CEFE250FD29FCA7" blockId="2.[477,1114,582,791]" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFFBFD6E4CEFE250FC43FDEA" bold="true" box="[477,967,582,603]" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">FIGURE 2. ESTIMATED EXTENSOR MUSCLE MASS</emphasis>
per leg needed to run fast, as a fraction of total body mass. Larger animals need relatively more leg muscle to run. This dependence is illustrated by the solid line, calculated for a chicken scaled up to the size of 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFFBFD6E4919E280FBBBFD1B" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[1067,1087,662,683]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="2" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFFBFD6E4919E280FBBBFD1B" box="[1067,1087,662,683]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">T.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
rex. For several models of 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFFBFD6E4FE9E2A7FC8BFD76" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[731,783,689,710]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="2" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFFBFD6E4FE9E2A7FC8BFD76" box="[731,783,689,710]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">T. rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
anatomy, the estimates (red) all require more leg muscle for running fast than the creature was likely to have had (orange dot). (Adapted from ref. 6.)
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFFBFD6E4D92E2E0FE41FB2A" blockId="2.[128,449,95,860]" lastBlockId="2.[128,545,864,1496]" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">Hutchinson and Garcia tested their running model with living species: a chicken (a fast runner) and an alligator (unable to run on two legs). The model predicted that a chicken must have at least 5% of its body weight as extensor muscles in each leg to run fast, almost a factor of two below the actual fraction of 9%. But for an alligator to run on its hind legs, the model predicted it would have to have a leg muscle fraction of 8%, and indeed alligators have much less than that. Thus in both cases, the model gave results consistent with observations.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFFBFD6E4D92E489FCCFFC3F" blockId="2.[128,545,864,1496]" lastBlockId="2.[576,993,862,1498]" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">For chickens and alligators, both distant relatives of extinct dinosaurs, the anatomical details the model required—joint angles, limb lengths, and weight distribution—were available from dissection. But for dinosaurs, only limb lengths are readily available from fossils. Weights can be estimated with various methods such as scaling, and by normalizing variables to total body mass, the researchers could reduce the effects of weight uncertainty. That left posture as the largest unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFFBFD6E4F52E382FD6FFB29" blockId="2.[576,993,862,1498]" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">
In what Andrew Biewener (Harvard University) calls a nice quanti- tative addition to their study, Hutchinson and Garcia examined various values for 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFFBFD6E4E1AE3E9FCE9FBA4" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[808,877,1023,1044]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="2" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFFBFD6E4E1AE3E9FCE9FBA4" box="[808,877,1023,1044]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">T. rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’s posture parameters, thereby getting a sense of the model’s sensitivity and uncertainty. The results for the different sets of values are shown as the solid red circles in 
<figureCitation id="14C018C5FFFBFD6E4FBCE492FD63FB29" box="[654,743,1156,1178]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[477,555,582,603]" captionTargetBox="[484,1113,99,567]" captionTargetId="graphics@2.[571,1099,104,523]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. ESTIMATED EXTENSOR MUSCLE MASS per leg needed to run fast, as a fraction of total body mass. Larger animals need relatively more leg muscle to run. This dependence is illustrated by the solid line, calculated for a chicken scaled up to the size of T. rex. For several models of T. rex anatomy, the estimates (red) all require more leg muscle for running fast than the creature was likely to have had (orange dot). (Adapted from ref. 6.)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3961004" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3961004/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">figure 2</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFFBFD6E4F52E489FAB1FE29" blockId="2.[576,993,862,1498]" lastBlockId="2.[1147,1441,95,858]" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">
The color bands of 
<figureCitation id="14C018C5FFFBFD6E4E0EE489FC10FB04" box="[828,916,1183,1205]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[477,555,582,603]" captionTargetBox="[484,1113,99,567]" captionTargetId="graphics@2.[571,1099,104,523]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. ESTIMATED EXTENSOR MUSCLE MASS per leg needed to run fast, as a fraction of total body mass. Larger animals need relatively more leg muscle to run. This dependence is illustrated by the solid line, calculated for a chicken scaled up to the size of T. rex. For several models of T. rex anatomy, the estimates (red) all require more leg muscle for running fast than the creature was likely to have had (orange dot). (Adapted from ref. 6.)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3961004" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3961004/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">figure 2</figureCitation>
follow from anatomical constraints and current knowledge of living animals. Having a leg muscle mass greater than 50% of the total body mass is impossible, because then the two legs combined would be more massive than the whole. For consistency with extant vertebrates, which have a total muscle mass that’s half their total body mass or less, the researchers also rule out running when the required leg muscle mass fraction is more than 25%. For required fractional muscle masses below 25%, running ability depends on the actual leg muscle mass, as for the alligator. Empirically, the most agile running bipeds don’t require more than 5% of their body weight to be leg extensor muscle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFFBFD6E49A9E18BFAA1FCBA" blockId="2.[1147,1441,95,858]" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">
“Despite fairly generous assumptions,” says Garcia, “muscle masses would need to be unreasonably high for 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFFBFD6E4872E211FA04FDAC" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[1344,1408,519,540]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="2" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFFBFD6E4872E211FA04FDAC" box="[1344,1408,519,540]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">T. rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to be a fast runner.” Even with the most favorable posture parameters, the researchers report that required extensor muscle is larger than the actual muscle mass of 7–10% they estimate based on scaling models.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFFBFD6E49A9E319FA14FC74" blockId="2.[1147,1441,95,858]" lastBlockId="2.[1024,1441,862,1175]" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">
Given the extensive unknowns, the pair hesitate to put a specific upper bound on the maximum speed of 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFFBFD6E48B9E349FBA6FC3F" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="2" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFFBFD6E48B9E349FBA6FC3F" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">T. rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. “Speeds of 11 m/s [25 mph] would be pushing it,” says Hutchinson, “but 20 m/s [45 mph] is not reasonable.”
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C440440FFFBFD6E4912E3DEFB0FFBCD" blockId="2.[1024,1441,862,1175]" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">
This work hasn’t settled the debate over 
<taxonomicName id="4BFB7FC3FFFBFD6E4907E3F2FBF4FC49" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[1077,1136,996,1017]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="2" pageNumber="19" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis id="BE8FD852FFFBFD6E4907E3F2FBF4FC49" box="[1077,1136,996,1017]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">T. rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
speed. Hutchinson is working on applying the model to other, larger living animals such as ostriches and rhinoceroses to test the conclusions, something many critics are eager to see.
</paragraph>
